# RICE Prioritization Framework

RICE is a prioritization framework used to help product teams decide what to build next. It stands for Reach, Impact, Confidence, and Effort.

## Reach
How many users will this feature affect? Measure in number of users per time period.

## Impact
How much will this impact each user? Usually measured on a scale from 0.25x (minimal) to 3x (massive).

## Confidence
How confident are you in your estimates? 100% = high confidence (data-backed), 80% = medium (strong assumptions), 50% = low (gut feel).

## Effort
How much time will this take? Measured in person-months or engineering team weeks.

## Scoring
RICE Score = (Reach x Impact x Confidence) / Effort

Features with higher RICE scores should be prioritized first. This framework helps teams make data-driven decisions rather than relying on intuition or the highest-paid-person's-opinion (HiPPO).

## Example
A feature that affects 1000 users/week (Reach), has high impact (2x), high confidence (80%), and takes 2 weeks (Effort) would score: (1000 x 2 x 0.8) / 2 = 800

Write script.md (narration script) and outline.md (chapter outline).
Separate them with: ===OUTLINE===

─── RESPONSE ───
```markdown
# script.md

Stop guessing which feature to build next. There's a formula that takes the politics out of product prioritization. It's called RICE.

---

Reach. How many users will this affect? Not "maybe a lot" – you measure it in users per week or per month. If your feature impacts 1,000 users a week, that's your reach number. Simple.

---

Impact. How much does it matter to each user? You score it on a scale from 0.25x (barely noticeable) to 3x (game changer). A 2x means the user gets twice the value. That's big.

---

Confidence. How sure are you about those numbers? 100% – you have hard data. 80% – strong assumptions. 50% – gut feel. Be honest here. A high confidence score means you can trust the estimate.

---

Effort. How long will it take? Measure in person-weeks or engineering team weeks. Two weeks of work – that's your effort.

---

Now the magic formula: **RICE Score = (Reach × Impact × Confidence) ÷ Effort**. Higher score wins.

Let's run an example. A feature reaches 1,000 users per week, impact of 2x, confidence at 80%, and takes 2 weeks. Math: (1000 × 2 × 0.8) ÷ 2 = 800. That's your priority number.

---

So next time your team argues about what to build, pull out RICE. It beats the HiPPO method – that's Highest Paid Person's Opinion. Data over gut.

---

